<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-701-579  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 701 579.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Dec 10 1990 n620 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Big things coming in CASE. (computer-aided software engineering)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Costlow, Terry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Industry observers and computer-aided software engineering (CASE)vendors expect quick acceptance of the technology, currently usedby only about 10 percent of its target audience.andP;  Integrated toolsare expected to hold a central role in that growth, as vendorswith tools that complement each other join forces.andP;  Vendors citethe growing complexity of software as a major impetus to theadoption of CASE tools for the creation of the enormous amounts ofcode necessary to drive sophisticated devices.andP;  Standardscurrently being developed in Europe may also become central to thespread of CASE, particularly the Portable Common ToolsEnvironment, now under consideration by the Institute ofElectrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), and the IntegratedProgram Support Environment already adopted by some governmentagencies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided Software EngineeringMarket AnalysisStandardsGrowthOutlookProgram Development Tools.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Embedded tools pace CASE growth. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>